Create normalization function

normalize = function(x){
  return ((x-min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x)))}

Success Measure, that equally weighs an app’s number of ratings with the app’s average rating and gives it a score between 0 and 1, with a value of 1 being the best. 

# Create log of rating_count with +1 correction
app <- app %>% mutate(rating_count_log = log(app$rating_count + 1))

# Normalize rating count
app <- app %>% mutate(rcl_norm = normalize(rating_count_log))

# Normalize average rating
app <- app %>% mutate(ar_norm = normalize(average_rating))

# Create target variable with mean of normalized average_rating and log(rating_count)
app <- app %>% mutate(target = rcl_norm * ar_norm)

# Remove old measures and intermediary calculations
app <- subset(app, select= (-c(rating_count, average_rating, rcl_norm, rating_count_log, ar_norm)))

Interperation from Approach: We use number of ratings as a proxy for downloads and engagement,and average rating account for how satisfied customers were with each app.

To find natural pattern in the dataset

set.seed(42)
# Use map_dbl to run many models with varying value of k (centers)
tot_withinss <- map_dbl(1:10,  function(k){
  model <- kmeans(x =app_norm, centers = k)
  model$tot.withinss
})

# Generate a data frame containing both k and tot_withinss
elbow_df <- data.frame(
  k = 1:10,
  tot_withinss = tot_withinss
)

# Plot the elbow plot
ggplot(elbow_df, aes(x = k, y = tot_withinss)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:10)

Conclusions from Approach: We choose elbow point where k equals 6.

  select(app_store, category, is_US, target) %>% 
  group_by(app_store, is_US, category) %>%
  summarise(target = mean(target))

App performance for Categories on Apple Store

To show the difference between application with in-app ads and without in-app ads

new_data = app %>% arrange(desc(target)) %>% slice(1:100)
t.test(new_data$in_app_ads, app$in_app_ads)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  new_data$in_app_ads and app$in_app_ads
## t = 5.3328, df = 99.72, p-value = 6.045e-07
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.1658348 0.3623373
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  0.590000  0.325914
new_data1 = app %>% filter(in_app_ads == 0)
new_data2 = app %>% filter(in_app_ads == 1)
t.test(new_data1$target, new_data2$target)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  new_data1$target and new_data2$target

## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0

##  -0.07922225 -0.07042321
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 0.3624402 0.4372630

Interperation from Approach: The difference in means between application with in-app ads and without in-app ads are significantly different Conclusions from Approach: As the mean of the success measure for apps with in-app ads is higher than the apps without in-app ads.There is a high user satisfaction even though there are in-app ads in the education category.
